Introduction

In this study, series of hourly produced solar energy from a solar plant in Turkey will be analyzed with appropriate statistical tools. Moreover, based on the findings, forecasting models powered by time series and regression approaches will be constructed. The regression models will be evaluated based on residual standard error and goodness of fit while the models using time series methods will be evaluated by metrics such as AICc and BIC. At last, one model from each approach will be selected and tested on a specified period while dynamically changing the model parameters by use of the observations till two days before the forecast of a day in test period.

It should be stated that, although the main aim is to provide hourly forecasts for the pre-determined days, the statistical analysis and comments are much more valuable than the mere forecast performance since these make this study more scientific.

The data provided for the study consists of hourly produced energy by the solar plant named NIGDE CINGILLI GES in the period from 09-10-2019 till 02-02-2021. The production amounts are gathered along with average temperature, downward radiation flux and total cloud cover from 4 different measurement centers nearby the plant.

To begin with the analysis, the data should be brought to appropriate format, renaming the columns by the abbreviations the data can be seen as,

It should be sensible to plot the hourly time series after this point,

From the plot it can be observed that there are much variation in the series, since this is a solar plant there are many hours, mostly in night time, with zero production. Moreover, there is volatility present even in points that can be considered to be close in time this is due to the nature of the series being affected profoundly by weather conditions, so even small changes in conditions may lead to observable differences in production behavior of the plant. Although it can be argued that the plot reveals a yearly seasonality or cyclic behavior, it might be a better idea to visualize daily aggregated series to discuss this seasonality,

## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)

This plot shows the daily summed amount of production of the solar plant in time. It can be claimed that the production volume decreases from summer to winter and increases back from winter to summer. From the last few months’ observations visualized in the right part of the graph, it can be predicted that the series will exhibit a behavior similar to the one occurred in transition from summer to winter in 2019. Though the seasonality is clearly existent, there are two important observations that can be mentioned before continuing the analyses. Firstly, the seasonality may not be entirely the same in different years, the behaviors and levels, shape or rate at which the production values increase or decrease may vary. This might be related to the factors of weather conditions of which some are included in the dataset and be monitored with the data in regression analysis part. Secondly, it can be stated that the variance in summer time is comparably less than the variance in other seasons. This situation might have arose due to the more stable and higher temperatures and amount of sun shine duration in summer. As a result, this decreasing variance in summer season exists in the nature of the problem and although it may violate some assumptions of the models to be constructed, it is still hard to eliminate the behavior from the problem.

From the autocorrelation function of the hourly series, it is obvious that the series exhibit a daily seasonality. In other words, there is high extent of positive correlation between same hours of consecutive days. Furthermore, as the difference between hours increases the correlation coefficient increases. This reveals that there are continuous periods in days in which hours show similar behavior in terms of solar energy production. This can be explained by the tendency of weather conditions to be similar in short runs for periods of days such as morning and evening. Moving on with auto-correlation function of daily series,

The results are surprising. There is always a positive correlation between the production amounts of days that are close in a year. Although from the other series of energy domain, weekly seasonality can be expected, these series reveal no such pattern. This might be because the consumption or imbalance amounts are determined based on the human actors and in defined settings such as work-days, holidays, and weekends. However, if there are no outside factors affecting production in solar plants, such as rules of close up, change or cleaning etc., it would have been naïve to expect solar production to behave in same manner. The plot on the other hand, shows signals of weak positive partial auto-correlation on 5, 6 or 11 days basis along with lag 1 since in some multiples of these numbers, the auto-correlations attains a local maxima. If partial auto-correlation function is extracted,

There are several lags in which the level of partial auto-correlation cannot be ignored. Although positive partial serial correlations at small lags seem reasonable because of continuity/similarity in weather conditions, positive correlation at lag 11 is undeniably above the significant threshold. Though a small inspection of related literatures have been carried out to find an explanation, there is no evidence of such behavior in other solar production environments. Nevertheless, since the partial auto-correlation is significant, it will be assumed in the rest of the study that the relation is existent in the production environment of CINGILLI GES maybe because of a regulation related to plant. Lastly, from this comprehensive analysis it can be inferred that the hourly production levels show a daily seasonality, whereas daily aggregated levels show a weak yearly seasonality, with special relation at lag 11.

If the histogram of the production amounts can be visualized,

On the first glance, the histogram seems to be coming from an exponential distribution. The accumulation near zero is expected since even in the days with longest sunshine duration, there are many dark hours. If those 0 values were to be extracted from the data, the shape of the distribution will resemble that of a uniform distribution. In several studies conducted before, the main assumption was the normality of observations however in this setting there is no such difference. It can be suspected whether this might hinder the model construction and worsen the model performance in the long run.

Before moving on building models, stationary of the series can be discussed. From the changing mean levels created by seasonality, changing variance and significant auto-correlations at several lags; it is impossible to conclude that the series are stationary. In fact, if Unit Root Test is imposed on the series,

## 
## ####################### 
## # KPSS Unit Root Test # 
## #######################

## critical values 0.347 0.463  0.574 0.739

It is revealed that the test statistic is larger than the critical threshold on all significance levels, leading to reject the null hypothesis of series being stationary.

For both time series and regression methods, there are various techniques related to aggregation and disaggregation of the data. Moreover, choice of aggregation, in other words predicting the total production and separating this amount to hourly levels via use of previous data, is also up to the analyst. To sum up, there are actually three principal approaches that will be discussed briefly. From these approaches, by keeping the nature of the problem and forecasting mechanics, appropriate approach for time series decomposition and regression analyses will be selected.

Studying with hourly time series is possible in both methods. In pure time series prediction models, frequency can be selected as 24 for decomposition since daily seasonality is obvious, the models can be powered by differencing at certain lags or ARIMA models. However, production in boundary hours, early morning or early evening, might change from season to season. Although deleting hours with zero production is possible, this may distort the serial correlation calculations leading to future violated assumptions or worsened performance of the model. Differencing the series on 24 or 48 hours might be a more suitable approach on this case since the change in the levels are seem more stable, resembling more of a stationary distribution.

On the regression side, since the approach is entirely data-based it is possible for the coefficients in those boundary hours to be close to zero. Nonetheless, these errors may in the long run hinder the performance of the model. Because the hours in which production start and cease change from season to season, composed variables of month and hour can be used such as Hour 7 of Month 6 or Hour 9 or Season 2. Yet, use of such regressors might complicate the matters since this becomes a more advanced approach compared to the scope of this study. By examination of production start and end in various months or seasons, eliminating those hours from the regression model, later to give 0 forecast to these hours is also a technique that will be used in this study.

Partitioning the hourly time series by hour windows into 24 different daily series is a second well-known technique. In this study, use of this approach is discarded to keep the study on point and not disturb the discussion with 24 different models for each hour. However, in a work environment, use of such models might lead to better performance since there is specialization for every hour level. Although it will not be used in the analysis, the approach may also lead to difficulties if lagged cross correlations with lots of exogenous variables are considered.

A final method can be to construct daily production time series prediction models later to disaggregate the findings into hours by use of linear regression or means analysis using the past data itself. Though this method is highly suitable and practical for the general consumption levels, the solar production is not bound or regulated with human defined factors. The hourly production percentages will probably be approximated roughly leading to inadequate model performance. Nevertheless, considering the prediction environment this method is selected as suitable for the time-series and ARIMA models.

Time Series Approaches

As mentioned before, there are several paths that can be chosen for the model construction. In prior studies by the analyst, models powered by pure differencing and ARIMA were explored with data from other domains, this time it can be a good idea to go with time series decomposition, building differencing and ARIMA on the random component. If hourly data is selected for this task, since the possibility of model for each hour is ruled out, this leads to 48 step ahead ARIMA calculations. Moreover, the models found by the auto.arima function keep smoothing the forecasted random noise that in few steps, the random noise converges to zero. As continuing with hourly series is rather hard keeping in mind the forecasting setting, aggregating the series to daily level by use of sum function to create a daily model might be a more suitable approach.

Keeping in mind the serial correlation function of the daily series before, to decompose the data seasonality of 11 is selected. It should be noted that this selection might be subject to some doubt, however there are not any lags in which the auto-correlation is said to be profound in related literature. Moreover, it is decided by analyst to keep the auto-correlations at small lags in the data for further differencing before building and searching for ARIMA models. If the series are decomposed in this manner,

It can be seen that a seasonal component is found and remaining assumed random noise seems stationary excluding the summer time which is a situation in the nature of the problem as discussed before. If a KPSS test is executed,

It can be claimed that the normality assumption is violated within the random series. The series being somehow left-skewed with mode greater than supposed mean, which is 0. To see if differentiation might reveal better fit for normal distribution, ACF plot can be drawn,

There seems to occur weak positive serial correlation at lag 1 and some negative serial correlations at following lags till 5. To examine the relations in a more clear environment,

If lag 1 is eliminated, there is revealed to be negative partial correlations in most lags. Although differencing the series by using lagged observations from the predecessor of the period is can lead to a more improved model, keeping in mind the prediction setting this might complicate the forecast part of the story. Moreover, using predictions to construct predictions may reduce the performance of the model.

For differencing two branches are considered by the researcher. One of the differencing approaches will use an aggregated value of lag 2 and lag 3 to difference the random component with. The other method will make use of lag 4 random observation in addition to these. It should be kept in mind that the tuning of differentiation parameters are carried out with respect to auto-correlation weights on these lags. Moreover, several pairs of coefficients are selected and tried out on the series iteratively. It is suitable to state that since the serial correlations have found to be negative, the smoothed random components are added on top of the random component in this process.

As for utilization of lag 2 along with lag 3, coefficients of 0.15 and 0.25 are selected. Other coefficients in neighborhood of these are found to be increasing serial correlations to a significant level on the positive side. Of course, more advanced and detailed parameter selection might have been carried out. With this differentiation the series are,

Linear Regression

Before elaborating on linear regression, plot of the data points in time can be re-drawn,

On the regression side, hourly series regression will be selected as of method. From inspection of dataset, examining the monthly mean hourly production amounts and use of geography knowledge, certain hours in certain months are ruled out from the dataset, later to be filled with zero forecasts. List of these hours can be found in code.

As discussed before, after the exclusion of these hours a histogram of the remaining observations and resembling that of uniform distribution or inverse normal distribution, if exists, can be shown,

First of all, from the discussions made earlier it is reasonable to think that the series show a micro (daily) and a macro (yearly) seasonality. Daily seasonality can be easily modelled by use of factorization of hours remaining within the dataset. For modelling the yearly seasonality various paths can be taken. For example, roughly a year can be assumed to be consisting of 2 runs, one increasing and one decreasing and constant periods in between. However, modeling this may become an oversimplification as there are constant or opposing periods within the runs itself. Instead of this, factorization of months can be used. Model Testing and Brief Comments

By use of some statistics, some comments can be made about the obtained forecasts for the test period. For the linear regression model, some stats are,

##      n    mean       sd     FBias      MAD    WMAPE
## 1 1488 4.75705 8.160993 0.1352593 2.116811 0.444984

The WMAPE is much high and it can be concluded that the performance of the model is not much satisfactory. This actually is a surprising result as the model yielded a good enough performance on the train period. However, it should be noted that production of solar energy is rather random and since the produced values are small, a small residual might contribute as a high percentage to the WMAPE. If the performance of the ARIMA powered model on the test period is gathered,

##      n    mean       sd      FBias      MAD     WMAPE
## 1 1488 4.75705 8.160993 0.01130007 2.253883 0.4737985

The WMAPE has become much higher and performance has been worsened. This is actually expected as this model only makes use of a questionable seasonality and differencing related to some weak auto-correlations. In general use of exogenous variables can yield better performance for the prediction of producing solar energy. However, it should be stated that the prior model tend to over predict the production amounts while for this model on average the residuals are closer to zero.

Conclusion

Predicting the hourly solar energy production series is a hard and rather tedious job. The series are not bound or regulated by any human intervention so most seasonality are only weak. Furthermore, there are several factors that are related to weather conditions. In a prediction setting, where predictions are made considering 36 hours ahead; trusting on the weather forecasts might already be misleading. Moreover, the extent of correlations change from season to season leading to future complications and adjustment.

Series being hourly is also another problem as in some hours there are small productions whereas in the same hours next or previous days there might be no production. It can be stated that from hourly series side, a model with significantly satisfactory training performance might face reduced performance in a test period. There are more advanced techniques to apply such as building models for each hour or using exponential smoothing. Nevertheless, it should be noted that the aim of this work is not to provide pure forecasts but to discuss series within the forecasting domain and state possible approaches, improvements or shortcomings.

In this study two different methods to predict hourly series are used. Keeping all the previous discussion in mind, selecting linear regression to predict hourly amount of solar plant production seems more reasonable for some reasons. First of all, the interest variable is correlated to some exogenous variables with changing extent thorough the year and more advanced use of these variables may lead to an improved performance. An addition to exogenous variables can be that if there occurs extreme situations with temperature or cloud layers in an unexpected period of the year, the effects are better and possibly faster brought to the predictions. Time series on the other hand may delay the effect of these unprecedented situations leading to distortion in both current and future values since these can be seen as errors to smoothed or lagged. Lastly, the seasonality used in the time series decomposition might be artificial and may not be existent in the future as there are no reasonable seasonality other than weakly annual one for the daily series.
